  \section{Introduction}
    \label{sec:intro}
    The T-V distinction traditionally refers to a contrast in pronominal forms of address that is constrained by the power relationship between two speakers as well as their social solidarity or lack thereof \citep{brown_pronouns_1960}. For example, English speakers once employed either \emph{thou} or \emph{you/ye} as a subject pronoun when addressing their interlocutor, which \citet{brown_pronouns_1960} supposed to have been based on whether the interlocutor was familiar or someone from whom they wanted to maintain a polite distance (p.~252). The phenomenon in European languages is assumed to stem from its existence in Latin, in which the respective pronouns were \emph{tu} and \emph{vos}, hence ``T-V'' \citep[p.~254]{brown_pronouns_1960}. Today, the T-V distinction is still a salient component of French in the form of the pronouns \emph{tu} and \emph{vous}, matching the initial letters of the earlier Latin pronouns.

    The interpretation of the T-V distinction in French has at times been challenged, however. \citet{brown_pronouns_1960} set the stage for the debate by introducing the idea that the choice of terms of address could be boiled down to power and solidarity. Their argument was mostly based on their own intuitive reasoning, though they did carry out a survey questionnaire to learn more about which second person pronouns upper-class men in France choose using a Likert scale \citep[pp.~262-263]{brown_pronouns_1960}. Their results showed that in only 11\% of hypothetical encounters between social unequals did respondants claim that the choice of \emph{tu} or \emph{vous} would not be reciprocal \citep[p.~261]{brown_pronouns_1960}. They concluded from this that solidarity had become the most important factor in choosing terms of address by that time. This means that they did not present this information as proof of their interpretation but as an example of the application of their interpretation. Still, the information they provided is useful for understanding the distribution of \emph{tu} versus \emph{vous}.

    Several years later, \citet{lambert_use_1967} conducted a similar survey with teenage males in Quebec City. His questionnaires simply asked respondants to identify which pronouns they use and receive with different interlocutors. The results also showed reciprocity between friends and between strangers in public but clear non-reciprocity with grandparents and extended family \citep[p.~615]{lambert_use_1967}. Once again, \citeauthor{lambert_use_1967}'s results did not provide direct evidence for the validity of \citeauthor{brown_pronouns_1960}'s interpretation of the T-V distinction, but he was able to use the ideas of power and solidarity to effectively explain the distribution he found.

    Much later on, \citet{morford_social_1997} argued extensively against the idea that power and solidarity alone can explain the choice of terms of address in French. She claimed that this two factors oversimplify the dynamics of interactions, which she supported with extensive ethnographic data. For instance, one of her informants explained that her parents went to lengths to address all friends with \emph{tu} as a sort of liberal political stance rather than as an effort to recognize power relations or create solidarity \citep[pp.~19-20]{morford_social_1997}. However, while \citeauthor{morford_social_1997} successfully highlighted the complexity of pronoun choice in French, it is not entirely clear that such stances cannot be characterized purely in terms of power and solidarity. Indeed, the idea in this case seems to be that liberals in France value egalitarianism and hence solidarity.

    The studies mentioned above in part focused on the appropriate way to interpret the T-V distinction in French and in part provided some evidence for how \emph{tu} and \emph{vous} are distributed socially. However, there is still much that can be learned by performing more quantitative analyses of pronoun choice. For instance, while survey questionnaires have the advantage of being able to capture a wide breadth of social classes, some important broad social classes were left out of these studies, such as women. Survey questionnaires also rely entirely on self-reported usage. In the case of a fairly overt variable like T-V choice, self-reported usage may in fact be accurate, but it could still be beneficial to look at language in use to ascertain how T-V choice plays out when speakers are not making a conscious effort to think about which pronouns they are using. The objective in the current study is thus to carry out a quantitative analysis of the social factors that may or may not play a role in the use of \emph{tu} versus \emph{vous} in natural conversations. Specifically, I ask the following question:
    \begin{itemize}
      \item[RQ:] Do speakers in the Nijmegen Corpus of Casual French differ in their T-V usage according to gender, region, and/or age?
    \end{itemize}
  \section{Methodology}
    \label{sec:method}
    The data for this study comes from the Nijmegen Corpus of Casual French (NCCFr) \citep{torreira_nijmegen_2010}. There were 46 participants who were recorded in pairs for the NCCFr, though \Sexpr{46 - nrow(tv[!duplicated(tv$SPEAKER),])} produced no tokens of second person singular pronouns and so were not included in the present analysis. The process involved a confederates who were students at the University of Paris 3 Sorbonne Nouvelle each recruiting two friends to participate. All three would begin conversing in a room without any researchers present until the confederate was called out by a researcher under the guise of having to fix a malfunctioning microphone. The two participants remained in the room and continued to have normal discussions for roughly 40 minutes. This section of the procedure was recorded and makes up the actual corpus.

    The participants were not only friends but were also the same gender, by design. Confederates were instructed to recruit two friends who shared their own gender. Naturally, due to the confederates being college age, the participants were almost all \Sexpr{min(tv$AGE)} to \Sexpr{levels(as.factor(tv$AGE))[length(levels(as.factor(tv$AGE))) - 2]} years old, only one being \Sexpr{levels(as.factor(tv$AGE))[length(levels(as.factor(tv$AGE))) - 1]} and one being \Sexpr{levels(as.factor(tv$AGE))[length(levels(as.factor(tv$AGE)))]}. Of the participants included in the present analysis, \Sexpr{nrow(tv[!duplicated(tv$SPEAKER) & tv$REGION == "Paris",])} were also from the Paris metropolitan area, the rest being from cities and towns in northern France. The speakers were however balanced for gender.
    
    The NCCFr has typically been used in phonetic studies and computational linguistic studies. The fact that the corpus is an audio corpus has facilitated its use in phonetic studies \citep[e.g.,][]{torreira_vowel_2011, torreira_realization_2011}. However, the corpus also contains video recordings of the conversations that took place, leading to the incorporation of visual data in at least one phonetic study \citep{torreira_phonetic_2015}. Additionally, the corpus has been used in research on speech recognition \citep[e.g.,][]{rouas_comparaison_2010}.
    
    However, the NCCFr is also appropriate for sociolinguistic studies. The fact that the recordings are of speech in a natural setting means that the resulting data is similar to what would typically be collected through sociolinguistic interviews. The creators of the corpus also included several social characteristics of the participants, those being their gender, ages, and regions of origin. While economic and ethnic details are left out, and while the ages do not cover a broad range, these details are at least good enough to get some preliminary sociolinguistic results to prepare for conducting larger studies.
    
    The corpus was thus coded for gender, age, and region of origin. Gender included both male and female, and age is given in years, meaning it is treated as a quantitative variable in the current analysis. The region of origin includes the \emph{ÃŽle-de-France}, roughly equivalent the Paris metropolitan area, and several regions of northern France, specifically Poitou-Charentes, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Limousin, Centre-Val de Loire, Upper Normandy, Lower Normandy, Burgundy, and Brittany. Naturally, the description of northern France here is fairly loose. Since the number of participants from each of these regions is not great, they have been collapsed into one group for the present analysis, called simply ``not Paris''.
    
    Linguistically, only the response variable (T-V) was coded for. This is due to the very large number of tokens ($n =$ \Sexpr{nrow(tv)}) and the limited amount of time available to code by hand. Technically, (T-V) includes different cases for both \emph{vous} and \emph{tu}. The former, however, is identical in all cases: always \emph{vous}. The latter, however, takes the form of \emph{tu} in subject position, \emph{te} as the object of a verb, and \emph{toi} as either a disjunctive pronoun or as the object of a preposition. These three forms were collapsed into \emph{tu} for two reasons: 1) I assumed that speakers would not oscillate between \emph{tu} and \emph{vous} within any single clause, and the real interest here is which term of address is being used in most utterances, and 2) coding \emph{vous} for case as well would require manual coding, which was impractical for the given analysis considering the number of tokens and time constraints.
    
    Tokens of (T-V) themselves were extracted from the corpus transcripts using a \lstinline|bash| script. The central piece of the script is a regular expression in of the form \lstinline+^(\-?tu|toi|te|t'|\-?vous)$+ which eventually outputs to a csv file. I considered this regex sufficient to extract all tokens as the corpus was transcribed in typical prescriptivist style writing so that, for example, \orth{vs} for \orth{vous} is not likely to be in the transcription as this is normally used in casual writing in text messaging and on services such as Twitter.
    
    The model used in the analysis of (T-V) realization in the NCCFr was a binomial logistic regression model. The response variable was (T-V) and the factors included in the model were gender, region, and age. The hypotheses for the model were non-directional:
    \begin{itemize}
      \item[$H_0$:] Gender, region, and age have no impact on the realization of (T-V).
      \item[$H_A$:] Gender, region, and/or age \emph{do} have an impact on the realization of (T-V).
    \end{itemize}
    The $\alpha$ level for these hypothesis tests is set to 0.05.
    
    While these non-directional hypotheses are indicative of my lack of position on the expected results, I do still have some expectations in terms of the general distribution of (T-V). As the literature suggests \citep[e.g.,][p.~615]{lambert_use_1967}, friends tend to use \emph{tu} reciprocally amongst each other. While this does not rule out the possibility of differences in the realization as \emph{vous} between subgroups of the participants, it would not be surprising to find that \emph{vous} is generally rare.
