    Additionally, interactions between factors were checked. As can be seen in Table \ref{tab:ints}, none of the models that included all factors with any combination of interactions were significantly different from the model that includes all factors without any specified interactions. This suggests that interactions are not coloring the results that would lead me to remove region and age from the model.
    
    Surprisingly, performing an ANOVA to compare the final model and the initial model that includes all factors suggests that these models are not significantly different (\Sexpr{round_any(tv.glm.anova$`Pr(>Chi)`[2], 0.001, ceiling)}). However, since every other model selection metric that was checked in this analysis suggested that only gender should be kept in the model, I decided to stick to that model, which finally looks like the following:
